message.content: We begin by rewriting $12$ and $18$ in terms of their prime factorizations. We have $12 = 2^2 \cdot 3$ and $18 = 2 \cdot 3^2$. Substituting into $12^2 \cdot 18^3$ gives $\begin{aligned} (2^2\cdot 3)^2 \cdot (2\cdot 3^2)^3 &= 2^4 \cdot 3^2 \cdot 2^3 \cdot 3^6 \\ &= 2^{4+3} \cdot 3^{2+6}\\ &= 2^7 \cdot 3^8. \end{aligned}$This means $x=7$ and $y=8$, and $x+y = \boxed{15}$.
